WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much for coming today.
I'm pleased to have with us Hugh Raffles this

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:08.220
afternoon.
Hugh is a professor and Chair of Anthropology

00:00:08.220 --> 00:00:13.720
at The New School.
And he's also the author of In Amazonia: A

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:17.310
Natural History for which
he received the Victor Turner Prize in Ethnographic

00:00:17.310 --> 00:00:20.670
Writing.
And his work in general addresses human concepts

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:24.039
of nature and the
relationship between humans, animals, and

00:00:24.039 --> 00:00:27.380
other non-humans.
And his most recent book is Insectopedia,

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:31.600
which a collection of 26
chapters one for each letter of the alphabet

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:35.180
in which he considers
insects and our cultural relation to them.

00:00:35.180 --> 00:00:41.510
Moving from cricket fighting in China to dances
with bees from insects

00:00:41.510 --> 00:00:45.190
at 15,000 feet to fighting fruit flies.
He's written a very engaging exploration of

00:00:45.190 --> 00:00:47.339
our relationship to the
physical world.

00:00:47.339 --> 00:00:51.639
So please join me in welcoming Hugh Raffles.

00:00:51.639 --> 00:00:52.639
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:52.639 --> 00:00:55.260
Hugh Raffles: Thanks.
Thanks very much, Simon.

00:00:55.260 --> 00:01:00.619
It's great to be here.
I'm very happy to be inside Google.

00:01:00.619 --> 00:01:04.210
It's really an interesting experience and
thank you very much for

00:01:04.210 --> 00:01:07.439
bringing me here.
What I'm going to do is talk a little bit

00:01:07.439 --> 00:01:08.909
about the book, tell you a
little bit about it.

00:01:08.909 --> 00:01:13.020
Then I'm going to read some -- a few sections
and then hopefully we'll

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:19.829
have time for some conversation afterwards.
So, um, as Simon said, this is a book about

00:01:19.829 --> 00:01:22.840
 -- a book about insects and
about human relationships to insects.

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:25.750
And it's very wide-ranging.
It covers -- it's historical.

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:30.600
It goes back to the 15th century and before.
There's actually some -- it actually takes

00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:35.179
us back to Aristotle in the
Western tradition.

00:01:35.179 --> 00:01:38.729
But it also is based around -- it also has
quite a bit about field work

00:01:38.729 --> 00:01:41.890
which I've done in different places.
I'm an anthropologist and I like to travel

00:01:41.890 --> 00:01:45.049
and meet people in a whole
range the places.

00:01:45.049 --> 00:01:46.340
Then that's represented in the book.

00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:51.780
[pause]

00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:53.560
And as I said I'm an anthropologist but I'm
not an entomologist.

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:55.710
And when I started working on the book, I
actually didn't know very

00:01:55.710 --> 00:01:59.170
much about insects at all.
I didn't pay them a lot of attention except

00:01:59.170 --> 00:02:02.479
when they forced their way
into my life as they're inclined to do in

00:02:02.479 --> 00:02:04.091
New York apartments, which is
what I live in.

00:02:04.091 --> 00:02:08.430
And I certainly didn't understand them.
They seemed completely mysterious, apart from

00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:11.069
mosquitoes I didn't
really have much of an idea of even what they

00:02:11.069 --> 00:02:15.040
wanted.
But insects are fascinating.

00:02:15.040 --> 00:02:18.760
And they took me over.
The more time I spent studying them, the more

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:20.599
 -- the more interested I
got in them.

00:02:20.599 --> 00:02:23.340
They're powerful; they're dangerous; they're
beautiful; mysterious;

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:27.720
they're difficult and much more.
And I discovered they're often at the center

00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:28.940
of very fascinating
worlds.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:34.810
Worlds that wouldn't exist without them.
An insect collector that I met in Tokyo, a

00:02:34.810 --> 00:02:39.870
man called Daisaburo Okumoto,
told me that insect lovers are anarchists.

00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:43.260
And I think that he meant that he loved these
impossible, unmanageable

00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:48.890
creature because they're impossible and unmanageable
not despite the

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:51.440
fact that they are.
And I learned a lot from spending time with

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:54.860
people like him who'd
thought deeply about insects and about their

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:57.920
place in our lives.
Insects live in a completely different world

00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:00.180
from us.
And it's one that we pay very little attention

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:04.150
to, but if we do start
to look, to listen, and to shift our sense

00:03:04.150 --> 00:03:08.430
of scale, as many of the
people that I write about do, we enter a universe

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:11.760
that can dramatically
enrich the one that most of us normally occupy.

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:15.810
And that's -- that's the theme that this book
starts with.

00:03:15.810 --> 00:03:19.730
It describes how scientists in the 1920s tried
to find out something

00:03:19.730 --> 00:03:22.780
about the lives of insects who were invading
cotton crops in the U.S.

00:03:22.780 --> 00:03:26.049
South.
They sent up planes to see if they could -- to

00:03:26.049 --> 00:03:30.400
see what they could find
out about insect migration.

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:34.329
And as I'll try to describe in this passage,
they found a lot more than

00:03:34.329 --> 00:03:35.329
they bargained for.

00:03:35.329 --> 00:03:41.760
[READING]
"There are only a few flies and wasps in that

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:45.909
first trap at Tallulah,
but over the next five years, the researchers

00:03:45.909 --> 00:03:49.379
flew more than 1300
sorties from the Louisiana airstrip and they

00:03:49.379 --> 00:03:52.790
captured tens of thousands
more insects in altitudes ranging from 20

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:56.700
to 15,000 feet.
They generated a long series of charts and

00:03:56.700 --> 00:04:01.210
tables, cataloging
individual insects as 700-named species, according

00:04:01.210 --> 00:04:03.939
to the height at
which they were collected, the time of day,

00:04:03.939 --> 00:04:07.549
the wind speed and
direction, the temperature, barometric pressure,

00:04:07.549 --> 00:04:12.439
humidity, dew point,
and many other physical variables.

00:04:12.439 --> 00:04:15.209
They already knew something about long distance
dispersal.

00:04:15.209 --> 00:04:18.220
They'd heard about butterflies and gnats,
water striders, leaf bugs,

00:04:18.220 --> 00:04:23.040
booklice and katydids sighted hundreds of
miles out on the open ocean.

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:26.190
About the aphids that Captain William Perry
had encountered on ice

00:04:26.190 --> 00:04:30.440
flows during his polar expedition of 1828,
and about those other aphids

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:34.410
that in 1925 made the 800-mile journey cross
the frigid, wind-swept

00:04:34.410 --> 00:04:40.380
Bering Sea in just 24 hours.
Still, they were taken aback by the enormous

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:43.600
quantities of animals they
were discovering in the air above Louisiana

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.750
and unashamedly astonished
by the heights at which they found them.

00:04:46.750 --> 00:04:51.080
All of a sudden, it seems, the heavens had
opened.

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:54.320
They estimated that at any given time of day
on any given day

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:58.670
throughout the year, the air column rising
from 50 to 14,000 feet above

00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:02.330
one square mile of Louisiana countryside contained
an average of 25

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:06.640
million insects and perhaps as many as 36
million.

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:09.920
They found ladybugs at 6,000 feet during the
daytime; striped cucumber

00:05:09.920 --> 00:05:15.690
beetles at 3,000 feet during the night.
They collected 3 scorpion flies at 5,000 feet;

00:05:15.690 --> 00:05:20.410
31 fruit flies between
200 and 3,000; a fungus gnat at 7,000 feet,

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:24.510
another at 10,000.
They trapped an anthrax-transmitting horsefly

00:05:24.510 --> 00:05:27.170
at 200 feet and another
at 1,000.

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:30.150
They caught wingless worker ants as high as
4,000 feet.

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:35.310
And 16 species of parasitic wasps at altitudes
of up to 5,000 feet.

00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:39.310
At 15,000 feet, probably the highest elevation
at which any specimen

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:43.090
has ever been taken above the surface of the
earth, they wrote, they

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:47.310
trapped a ballooning spider.
A feat that reminded them that spiders are

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:50.930
thought to have navigated
the globe on the trade winds and led one of

00:05:50.930 --> 00:05:54.490
them to write that the
younger-most spiders are more or less addicted

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:56.870
to this mode of
transportation.

00:05:56.870 --> 00:05:59.740
An image of excited little animals packing
their luggage that opened a

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:02.970
small eruption on the consensus around the
passivity of all this

00:06:02.970 --> 00:06:07.120
airborne movement.
And led to a subsequent observation that ballooning

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:10.690
spiders not only
climb up to an exposed site -- a tree, twig,

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:14.810
or flower, for instance,
stand on tiptoe, raise their abdomen, test

00:06:14.810 --> 00:06:18.190
the atmosphere, throw out
silk filaments and launch themselves into

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:22.420
a balloon or free, like
spread eagle, but that they also use their

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:25.610
bodies and their silk to
control their decent and the location of their

00:06:25.610 --> 00:06:29.860
landing.
36 million little animals flying unseen above

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:32.050
one square mile of
countryside.

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:36.130
The heavens opened.
The air column was a vault of insect-laden

00:06:36.130 --> 00:06:42.070
air from which fell a
continuous rain.

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:47.430
So stop, if you're inside, go to a window,
throw it open and turn your

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:51.820
face to the sky.
All that empty space, the deep vastness of

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:56.210
the air, the heavens wide
above you, the sky is full of insects and

00:06:56.210 --> 00:06:57.750
all of them are going
somewhere.

00:06:57.750 --> 00:07:01.450
Every day above and around us, their collective
voyage of billions of

00:07:01.450 --> 00:07:07.220
beings."
Well, that's -- that's sense of -- sort of

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:11.140
sense of mystery about there
being worlds around us that we're not -- that

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:13.500
we're not at all familiar
with is one of the themes that continues through

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:16.030
the book.
But quite a lot of the book, as I said, is

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:19.000
based field research that
I've done in various places.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.970
And I spent a few of the most enjoyable weeks
that I had in writing in

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:26.800
book in Shanghai.
And one of my chapters -- one of the chapters

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:30.520
in here is about people
there who train and fight crickets and people

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:33.680
who have a deep knowledge
about crickets.

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:36.050
Cricket fighting in China has a history that
goes back nearly a

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:38.620
thousand years and I go on to some detail
about this in the book.

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:42.930
And the part that I want to read you describes
some of what I learned

00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:45.860
from a very experienced cricket trainer that
I met there, a man called

00:07:45.860 --> 00:07:48.860
Master Fung, who was the director of a cricket
museum in Qi Bao which

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:58.330
is a suburb of Shanghai.
[Reading]

00:07:58.330 --> 00:08:01.940
"All these crickets were collected here in
Qi Bao, says Master Fung.

00:08:01.940 --> 00:08:06.050
Standing behind a table laden with hundreds
of great clay pots, each

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:09.550
containing one fighting male, and in some
cases, its female sex

00:08:09.550 --> 00:08:13.150
partner.
Qi Bao's crickets are famous throughout East

00:08:13.150 --> 00:08:15.910
Asia, he tells us, a
product of the township's rich soil.

00:08:15.910 --> 00:08:20.840
But since the fields here were built on in
the year 2000, crickets have

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:24.770
been harder to find.
Master Fung's two white-uniformed assistants

00:08:24.770 --> 00:08:27.630
fill the insect's
miniature water bottles with pipettes and

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.810
we humans all drink
pleasantly a stringent tea made from his recipe

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:34.329
of seven medicinal
herbs.

00:08:34.329 --> 00:08:37.189
Master Fung's considerable presence, the prim
of his white canvas hat

00:08:37.189 --> 00:08:40.969
rakishly angled, his jade pendant and rings,
his intense gaze, his

00:08:40.969 --> 00:08:45.740
animated storytelling, his throaty laugh.
Michael, my translator, and I are drawn to

00:08:45.740 --> 00:08:48.649
him immediately and hang on
his words.

00:08:48.649 --> 00:08:52.149
Master Fung is a cricket master, confides
his assistant Miss Jao.

00:08:52.149 --> 00:08:55.910
He has 40-years' experience.
There is no one more [INAUDIBLE, knowledgeable

00:08:55.910 --> 00:09:01.269
about] crickets.
Twenty years ago, everyone tells us, before

00:09:01.269 --> 00:09:04.840
the construction of the New
Shanghai gobbled up the landscape, in a time

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:08.410
when city neighborhoods
were patchworks of fields and houses, people

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:11.970
lived more intimately with
animal life.

00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:15.481
Many found companionship in cicadas or other
musical insects that they

00:09:15.481 --> 00:09:21.379
kept in bamboo cages and slim pocket boxes.
And young people, not just the middle-aged,

00:09:21.379 --> 00:09:26.360
played crickets, learning
how to recognize the three races and 72 personalities,

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.069
how to judge a
likely champion, how to train the fighters

00:09:29.069 --> 00:09:32.360
to their fullest potential.
How to use the pencil-thin brushes made of

00:09:32.360 --> 00:09:36.170
yard grass or mouse whisker
to stimulate the insects jaws and provoke

00:09:36.170 --> 00:09:40.079
them to combat.
They learned the rudiments of the three rudiments

00:09:40.079 --> 00:09:44.300
around which every
cricket manual is structured: Judging, training,

00:09:44.300 --> 00:09:49.540
and fighting.
When Master Fung and other experts tried to

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:52.019
instruct me in the
distinctions that allow them to judge a cricket's

00:09:52.019 --> 00:09:56.230
fighting potential,
they use a taxonomy that first appeared in

00:09:56.230 --> 00:10:01.080
Jia Shi-Dao's Book of Crickets,
a 900-year old manual of training and raising

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:06.220
crickets that's been
modified and supplemented but not overthrown

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:11.740
across the centuries.
The book outlines the fiercely complex system

00:10:11.740 --> 00:10:14.490
for classifying crickets.
It brings request body color.

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:19.990
Jia identifies and ranks four colors: Yellow,
red, black, and white.

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:25.350
By contrast, most cricket experts I talked
to in Shanghai describe only

00:10:25.350 --> 00:10:30.829
three colors: Yellow, green, and purple.
Yellow crickets are reputed to be the most

00:10:30.829 --> 00:10:34.790
aggressive of the three but
not necessarily the best fighters, because

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:38.740
green insects, though
quieter, are more strategic and according

00:10:38.740 --> 00:10:41.930
to the annual illustrated
list of cricket champions include a greater

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:46.920
number of generals.
Color is the first criterion by which crickets

00:10:46.920 --> 00:10:50.839
are divided and it
confers an initial identity, that is held

00:10:50.839 --> 00:10:54.649
to correspond to differences
in behavior and character.

00:10:54.649 --> 00:10:57.680
Below these gross distinctions, however, is
the further set of division

00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:03.810
into individual personalities whose total
number is often put at 72.

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:07.560
Below that, classification is based on an
agglomeration of numerous

00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:12.350
physical variables, complex clusters of characters,
length, shape, and

00:11:12.350 --> 00:11:16.009
color of the insect's legs and abdomen and
wings are all systematically

00:11:16.009 --> 00:11:21.220
passed, as is the shape of the head.
Current manuals might include seven or more

00:11:21.220 --> 00:11:26.509
possibilities and
differences in number, shape, color, and width

00:11:26.509 --> 00:11:29.540
of the fight lines that
run from front to back across the crown.

00:11:29.540 --> 00:11:35.290
Experts -- experts also consider the energy
of the antennae, the shape

00:11:35.290 --> 00:11:38.579
and color of the animal's eyebrows, which
should be opposite in color

00:11:38.579 --> 00:11:42.259
to the antennae.
The shape, color, translucence, and strength

00:11:42.259 --> 00:11:46.569
of the jaws, the shape and
size of the neck plate, the shape and resting

00:11:46.569 --> 00:11:50.920
angle of the forewings.
The sharpness of the tail tips, the hair on

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:54.629
the abdomen, the width of
the thorax and face, the thickness of the

00:11:54.629 --> 00:11:58.670
feet and the animal's overall
posture.

00:11:58.670 --> 00:12:02.160
The insect's skin must be dry, that is, it
must reflect light from

00:12:02.160 --> 00:12:07.720
inside itself not from the surface.
It must also be delicate, like a baby's.

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:12.180
The cricket's walk must be swift and easy.
It should not have a rolling gait.

00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:15.589
In general, strength is more important than
size.

00:12:15.589 --> 00:12:22.209
The quality of the jaw is decisive.
Master Fung tells us that the trainer's task

00:12:22.209 --> 00:12:26.010
is build on preexisting
natural virtues, to develop the animal's fighting

00:12:26.010 --> 00:12:29.779
spirit.
This indispensable quality is revealed only

00:12:29.779 --> 00:12:31.519
at the moment the insect
enters the arena.

00:12:31.519 --> 00:12:35.540
Though a cricket might look like a champion
in all respects, though the

00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:39.180
judgment of its physical qualities may be
correct, it can still turn

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:44.399
out to lack spirit in competition.
This, he insists, is less a matter of individual

00:12:44.399 --> 00:12:47.949
cricket's character
than a function of its care.

00:12:47.949 --> 00:12:50.200
It's the task of the trainer to buildup the
cricket's strength with

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:54.740
foods appropriate to its growth and individual
needs, to respond to its

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:57.889
sicknesses, develop its physical skills, cultivate
its virtues,

00:12:57.889 --> 00:13:01.600
overcome its natural aversion to light, and
habituate it to new, alien

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:05.800
surroundings.
Fundamentally, says Master Fung, a trainer

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:09.040
must create the conditions
in which the insect can be happy.

00:13:09.040 --> 00:13:12.809
A cricket knows when it is loved and it knows
when it's well cared for.

00:13:12.809 --> 00:13:17.339
And it responds in kind with loyalty, courage,
obedience, and the signs

00:13:17.339 --> 00:13:22.579
of quiet contentment.
In practical terms, this as quid pro quo,

00:13:22.579 --> 00:13:26.709
because a happy cricket is
amenable to training and as its health, skill,

00:13:26.709 --> 00:13:30.170
and confidence increase
under the trainer's care, so too does its

00:13:30.170 --> 00:13:35.420
fighting spirit.
And as he was explaining all this, describing

00:13:35.420 --> 00:13:39.180
the sexual regiment he
provides, outlining the many symptoms of ill-health

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:42.660
that one must be
alert to, displaying the purified water, the

00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:46.759
home-cooked foods, the
various parts, explaining that everything

00:13:46.759 --> 00:13:51.170
relies on communication and
that the yard grass is the bridge between

00:13:51.170 --> 00:13:54.519
him and the insect, that in
other words, they understand each other in

00:13:54.519 --> 00:13:58.759
a language beyond language.
Master Fung removed the lid from one of his

00:13:58.759 --> 00:14:02.319
pots and in an emphatic
response to my increasingly unimaginative

00:14:02.319 --> 00:14:06.061
line of questioning, took his
yard grass straw and barked orders at the

00:14:06.061 --> 00:14:09.019
cricket as if it as soldier
-- this way, that way.

00:14:09.019 --> 00:14:14.019
This way, that way.
And the insect, to Michael's and my real astonishment,

00:14:14.019 --> 00:14:17.709
responded
unhesitatingly turning left, right, left,

00:14:17.709 --> 00:14:21.329
right.
A routine of exercises that Master Fung eventually

00:14:21.329 --> 00:14:25.050
explained increases
the fighter's flexibility, makes him limber

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:29.199
and elastic, and shows that
man and insect understand each other through

00:14:29.199 --> 00:14:33.430
the language of command as
well as beyond it."

00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:41.540
So a significant part of the book is -- involves,
um, as I said,

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:48.939
involves fieldwork in various places.
But an equally large part of the book is involved

00:14:48.939 --> 00:14:52.399
with trying to think
through the ways that we -- the ways that

00:14:52.399 --> 00:14:56.619
humans think about insects
and the ways that insects enter our lives

00:14:56.619 --> 00:15:01.449
and enter our psyches in both
positive and negative ways.

