but when you put them together, then there's

00:29:52.870 --> 00:29:58.280
 -- there's some sort of
synergy that produces some greater intelligence

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:01.820
 -- intelligence that is
greater than any individual that there's something

00:30:01.820 --> 00:30:04.130
 -- and people
working in artificial intelligence have worked

00:30:04.130 --> 00:30:07.060
along these principles
in making -- and people work making robots,

00:30:07.060 --> 00:30:14.730
for instance.
I'm -- well, one -- let me give you one example

00:30:14.730 --> 00:30:19.870
of this that I find
kind of interesting which is work that a sound

00:30:19.870 --> 00:30:25.880
artist called David Dunn
has done with -- he's -- he's recorded, a

00:30:25.880 --> 00:30:31.220
few years ago, he recorded
the sounds of insects in ponds.

00:30:31.220 --> 00:30:34.030
And so a community of water insects inside
a pond.

00:30:34.030 --> 00:30:36.760
And at first, when you listen to his recording
and I guess I should say

00:30:36.760 --> 00:30:39.440
that first of all, I don't think anybody else
had ever done this before

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:43.220
which seems surprising.
But people have -- there's a very limited

00:30:43.220 --> 00:30:46.840
set of insects that people
have actually done research on and very little

00:30:46.840 --> 00:30:50.230
research has been done
on insect sound communication, even on insect

00:30:50.230 --> 00:30:54.110
hearing.
Because he's a sound artist obviously this

00:30:54.110 --> 00:30:55.610
is what he's been interested
in.

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:58.850
So he's recorded the sound of insects in ponds
and when you listen to

00:30:58.850 --> 00:31:05.070
it, at first -- at first you hear really a
lot of -- a lot of sort of

00:31:05.070 --> 00:31:11.230
unconnected, disparate kind of noises or sounds.
A lot of clicking and a lot of buzzing this

00:31:11.230 --> 00:31:15.250
sort of thing, whirring,
things that sound like static.

00:31:15.250 --> 00:31:17.550
And after time as it builds up and it's probably
the way he's put the

00:31:17.550 --> 00:31:20.840
recording together , but as it builds up , you
start to hear this very,

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:27.700
very complex -- very complex sort of polyrhythmic,
polyrhythmic sounds

00:31:27.700 --> 00:31:31.020
emerging.
And that you get a sense -- this sense of

00:31:31.020 --> 00:31:36.320
a very dense activity going
on.

00:31:36.320 --> 00:31:41.340
Now, as a musician, he interprets that as
this very high level of

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:45.570
communication that's happening.
He -- what he hears and it is -- he hears

00:31:45.570 --> 00:31:49.620
the rhythms in it, he hears
this complex rhythmic activity going on, and

00:31:49.620 --> 00:31:54.300
he hears some insects
responding to other insects.

00:31:54.300 --> 00:32:00.180
And he thinks of the pond itself as producing
some kind of -- or other

00:32:00.180 --> 00:32:04.060
community within the pond as producing some
sort of communicative

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:11.360
intelligence which is happening within that.
You know, this, of course, is very speculative.

00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:14.480
I'm -- you know, having done this research,
I'm very sympathetic to

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:18.370
these ideas.
The part of it that makes me pause a little

00:32:18.370 --> 00:32:21.020
is the assumption that's
often in there that individually these insects

00:32:21.020 --> 00:32:23.810
aren't particularly
interesting or these beings aren't particularly

00:32:23.810 --> 00:32:26.560
interesting, it's only
when they get together that something significant

00:32:26.560 --> 00:32:28.850
emerges out of the
collective.

00:32:28.850 --> 00:32:31.090
So I like the idea that something significant
emerges out of the

00:32:31.090 --> 00:32:35.450
collective, but I'm less convinced that individually
there's nothing

00:32:35.450 --> 00:32:38.500
going on.
And that they only have -- they only have

00:32:38.500 --> 00:32:41.240
any significance when you put
them together.

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:46.660
But there's -- there's certainly ways that
insects -- I guess we're

00:32:46.660 --> 00:32:51.610
talking about social insects here in general.
Well, actually, I'll get back to that.

00:32:51.610 --> 00:32:55.210
But in terms of social insects that collectively,
they're able to

00:32:55.210 --> 00:32:59.930
produce phenomenal things.
If you think of termite mounds or ants' nests

00:32:59.930 --> 00:33:04.340
or the kinds of decision
making processes that bees are able to go

00:33:04.340 --> 00:33:09.200
through -- there is --
there's the ability to cooperate to produce

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:13.070
remarkable collective,
collective efforts.

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:15.510
And there's just collective achievements that
they're able to do.

00:33:15.510 --> 00:33:18.990
And they're able to do it in general, say
within an individual hive or

00:33:18.990 --> 00:33:23.270
an individual nest in a very cooperative way.
I mean generally they're able to reach consensus

00:33:23.270 --> 00:33:28.900
after what appears to
be a process of debate and discussion.

00:33:28.900 --> 00:33:34.260
But it seems also that there's a lot of communication
that goes on

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:38.260
between insects of different species either
communication that is to

00:33:38.260 --> 00:33:44.170
warn other insects off and to, you know, sort
of defensive kinds of

00:33:44.170 --> 00:33:46.271
communication.
Or there's also kinds of communication that

00:33:46.271 --> 00:33:50.420
goes on to coordinate
behavior amongst species.

00:33:50.420 --> 00:33:54.990
And the communications [INAUDIBLE] on through
vibration, through chemical

00:33:54.990 --> 00:33:59.990
connections, all kinds of things.
And it's been a scenario which there's been

00:33:59.990 --> 00:34:01.950
very little research, I
think.

00:34:01.950 --> 00:34:06.310
But the parts fit -- that I've become quite
interested lately are the

00:34:06.310 --> 00:34:10.730
ones that people, ones that have investigated
by people who haven't

00:34:10.730 --> 00:34:16.480
had -- haven't had biological training so
much but have -- have brought

00:34:16.480 --> 00:34:18.349
ideas.
I mean particularly like David Dunn, who brought

00:34:18.349 --> 00:34:21.539
ideas from a different
domain, you know, as a musician.

00:34:21.539 --> 00:34:24.650
And he started to see -- started to see forms
of communication that

00:34:24.650 --> 00:34:29.359
have not been visible to insect scientists
who've been really caught up

00:34:29.359 --> 00:34:34.419
in chemical communication and looking at chemical
cues from pheromones,

00:34:34.419 --> 00:34:37.589
allomones and these kinds of things.
Cheromones.

00:34:37.589 --> 00:34:40.559
That's really dominated the study of insect
communication for the last

00:34:40.559 --> 00:34:46.269
30 or 40 years probably.
And so it's interesting to me that people

00:34:46.269 --> 00:34:48.860
who come with very, very
different training, very, very different way

00:34:48.860 --> 00:34:52.571
of thinking about it
they've started to be able to find new kinds,

00:34:52.571 --> 00:34:56.319
new kinds of interactions
that have just been outside the paradigm of

00:34:56.319 --> 00:35:01.740
investigation for the
last -- for the last period, anyway.

00:35:01.740 --> 00:35:04.720
Yeah.
Thank you.

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:10.369
&gt;&gt; I know you spent quite a bit of time in
the tropics when you were

00:35:10.369 --> 00:35:13.770
writing an earlier book Amazonia and I was
wondering if you have

00:35:13.770 --> 00:35:17.599
impressions from the your memories there about
whether there's a

00:35:17.599 --> 00:35:21.549
different place in the world that insects
have in the tropics than in

00:35:21.549 --> 00:35:24.401
where we live in the temperate zone and whether
the relationships

00:35:24.401 --> 00:35:28.770
between human and insects seem markedly different
thinking back on it

00:35:28.770 --> 00:35:29.770
in that way.

00:35:29.770 --> 00:35:32.150
Hugh Raffles: Yeah, that's a great question,
thank you.

00:35:32.150 --> 00:35:36.089
He's asking whether or not in -- the first
research that I did was in

00:35:36.089 --> 00:35:39.480
Amazonia, in a small community at the mouth
of the Amazon.

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:42.460
And he's asking whether or not there's a different
kind of relationship

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:46.910
that people with have insects there than you
would find -- you would

00:35:46.910 --> 00:35:52.670
find here and, um, in the tropics in general.
Well, one thing -- one thing that I've been

00:35:52.670 --> 00:35:58.170
thinking about recently in
that respect -- is that I'm not sure whether

00:35:58.170 --> 00:36:02.240
this answers the question
in the way that you'd want -- but people,

00:36:02.240 --> 00:36:07.059
you know, I've been struck by
as I've been going around and talking to people

00:36:07.059 --> 00:36:11.130
about this book, that
one of the topics that comes again and again

00:36:11.130 --> 00:36:14.690
is people's revulsion to
certain kind of insects, particularly to cockroaches.

00:36:14.690 --> 00:36:19.950
And people talk a lot about their instantaneous
 -- instantaneous

00:36:19.950 --> 00:36:22.609
reactions to just sort of lash out and crush
a roach.

00:36:22.609 --> 00:36:27.220
And I think this happens in -- I mean, I come
here from New York, but I

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:29.940
think it happens in California, too, but,
you know, there's this sort

00:36:29.940 --> 00:36:34.819
of immediate response.
And part of that I -- I think is because of

00:36:34.819 --> 00:36:37.640
the ways in which we
control, control our living space and our

00:36:37.640 --> 00:36:41.460
determination to keep it as
free from -- as free from the kinds of beings

00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:45.250
that we don't want in
there as possible and just sort to manage

00:36:45.250 --> 00:36:50.569
it in this very strict ways.
And when I was -- when I spent time in the

00:36:50.569 --> 00:36:53.940
Amazon, people had very
different relationship s, well, I'll say to

00:36:53.940 --> 00:36:56.680
cockroaches, particularly
but to things coming into their living space

00:36:56.680 --> 00:36:59.819
in general.
I mean unless they were animals which were

00:36:59.819 --> 00:37:04.240
actually going to cause them
personal, personal pain or other kinds of

00:37:04.240 --> 00:37:06.299
problems, they really weren't
too bothered by them.

00:37:06.299 --> 00:37:09.230
And also when I was living there, I wasn't
bothered by them either.

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:11.809
And partly that has to with the architecture
of the spaces.

00:37:11.809 --> 00:37:15.500
Space are much more open and they're much
more open to the elements as

00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:21.690
well, at least the ones that I was in.
So -- and people aren't trying to control

00:37:21.690 --> 00:37:24.470
what goes in and out in the
same kind of way.

00:37:24.470 --> 00:37:26.681
So, you know, if there was snakes came in
the house, you know,

00:37:26.681 --> 00:37:28.700
poisonous snakes, people were really bothered
by that.

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:32.500
When vampire bats came in the house at night,
people got very, very

00:37:32.500 --> 00:37:35.680
worked up about that, which was I was kind
of grateful for.

00:37:35.680 --> 00:37:39.420
And, you know, when there's mosquitoes at
certain times of the year,

00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:41.580
when you have like clouds of mosquitoes and
you can't even sit still

00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:46.390
because they're just biting you so badly,
then people took, you know,

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:50.559
as much action as they could against them.
And what we would do is set smoke off, going

00:37:50.559 --> 00:37:55.880
in their houses to just
try to get rid of them, which actually was

00:37:55.880 --> 00:37:58.460
almost as uncomfortable as
the mosquitoes themselves, right?

00:37:58.460 --> 00:38:01.940
But roaches and things like that?
You know, they don't really do us any harm,

00:38:01.940 --> 00:38:03.859
so nobody really was very
bothered by them.

00:38:03.859 --> 00:38:07.519
They just scuttled around and everybody just
ignored them.

00:38:07.519 --> 00:38:11.309
And so this is -- you know, I feel very strongly
this is a cultural

00:38:11.309 --> 00:38:15.040
reaction that we have to them.
It's not something that's hardwired as many

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:18.089
people argue because of the
shape of them and the way they move and stuff

00:38:18.089 --> 00:38:19.770
like that.
There's plenty of places that you can go to

00:38:19.770 --> 00:38:24.019
where people don't respond
to them in this aggressive and negative way.

00:38:24.019 --> 00:38:27.579
And it's fairly easy to train yourself not
to do that.

00:38:27.579 --> 00:38:30.700
But, you know, spend a bit of time looking
at them, seeing how

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:33.080
interesting they are and trying to, I suppose,
if you got an interest

00:38:33.080 --> 00:38:37.719
in it, trying to retain yourself not to respond
so immediately.

00:38:37.719 --> 00:38:45.170
&gt;&gt; So just one last question, which in reading
the book, a theme of

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:51.960
taxonomies keeps coming up and seeing the
world -- see the macro

00:38:51.960 --> 00:38:55.369
through the micro and vice versa.
And I was wondering if you could just speak

00:38:55.369 --> 00:38:59.160
a little bit more about
that and that way of seeing insects and seeing

00:38:59.160 --> 00:39:00.890
our sort of the world
around us.

00:39:00.890 --> 00:39:04.670
Hugh Raffles: Yeah, he's asking about taxonomy
in general and

00:39:04.670 --> 00:39:08.570
relationship between large things and small
things and seeing -- seeing

00:39:08.570 --> 00:39:12.099
large things out of looking closely at small
things.

00:39:12.099 --> 00:39:18.749
And -- I would say in terms of taxonomy one
thing that I think I've

00:39:18.749 --> 00:39:24.859
learned from the book is that we use the taxonomies
that we use the

00:39:24.859 --> 00:39:30.080
taxonomies that work for us.
So taxonomies seem to be -- I like to think

00:39:30.080 --> 00:39:31.440
we use the taxonomies that
work for us.

00:39:31.440 --> 00:39:38.390
Taxonomies are very -- are very instrumental.
So scientific taxonomy is a very useful thing

00:39:38.390 --> 00:39:41.619
if you're trying to
understand evolutionary relationships.

00:39:41.619 --> 00:39:45.001
And so it's a very useful thing if you want
to understand -- if you

00:39:45.001 --> 00:39:49.119
want to say develop conservation programs
and this kind of thing.

00:39:49.119 --> 00:39:52.289
But if that's not really your interest, if
you're interested instead,

00:39:52.289 --> 00:39:56.289
say, in training crickets to fight, then it's
not really much use to

00:39:56.289 --> 00:39:59.220
you to know that there are two species -- there
are two species of

00:39:59.220 --> 00:40:01.660
crickets.
And that's really what you need to know and

00:40:01.660 --> 00:40:04.522
then you want to protect
those crickets because this is their behavior

00:40:04.522 --> 00:40:06.239
and whatever.
It's much more useful to know that there are

00:40:06.239 --> 00:40:08.530
108 different -- I don't
know.

00:40:08.530 --> 00:40:12.450
108 different races and 72 personalities.
And they have these different qualities, which

00:40:12.450 --> 00:40:14.430
has no relationship --
you know, this is a classification system

00:40:14.430 --> 00:40:18.380
which is actually more much
complicated than a Linnaean -- Linnaean classification

00:40:18.380 --> 00:40:21.790
system and has
no relation to it but is much more useful

00:40:21.790 --> 00:40:25.950
if you're trying to train
crickets to fight or trying to judge crickets

00:40:25.950 --> 00:40:30.200
to fight.
So -- and of course in other -- in many places,

00:40:30.200 --> 00:40:33.329
people have
classification systems which rely on size.

00:40:33.329 --> 00:40:38.440
So they might classify things in a system
which would include insects.

00:40:38.440 --> 00:40:41.950
It might also include seashells or grains
of sand or other small things

00:40:41.950 --> 00:40:44.120
or say distant airplanes or something like
that.

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:48.150
That might be -- could be a system of tiny
things that move or tiny

00:40:48.150 --> 00:40:51.950
things that don't move or whatever.
And it partly depends on what you're trying

00:40:51.950 --> 00:40:53.369
to get out of system, what
it's useful for.

00:40:53.369 --> 00:41:00.710
That tends to be how we organize the world.
But -- but the other part of your question

00:41:00.710 --> 00:41:04.890
about finding large things
and small things, yeah.

00:41:04.890 --> 00:41:08.940
I think this is -- this is a very helpful
way to look -- to look at

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:13.710
this book and to think about what I've been
trying to do.

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:16.349
And again, I go back to tell you about somebody,
somebody who I talked

00:41:16.349 --> 00:41:19.690
to who had interesting ways of thinking about
this, which was a -- who

00:41:19.690 --> 00:41:24.010
was a -- somebody you might know, a neuroscientist,
a Japanese

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:27.859
neuroscientist named Yoro Takeshi.
He's well-known in Japan for -- not just for

00:41:27.859 --> 00:41:31.099
his neuroscience, but
because he's written these popular books of

00:41:31.099 --> 00:41:33.789
social criticism about
Japanese society.

00:41:33.789 --> 00:41:39.289
And he's also an insect collector.
And he collects weevils and other kinds of

00:41:39.289 --> 00:41:46.069
beetles.
And he has -- he talked about people, he talks

00:41:46.069 --> 00:41:49.930
about people having
mushy eyes, and mushy is a Japanese word for

00:41:49.930 --> 00:41:51.359
insects.
There's actually another type of classification

00:41:51.359 --> 00:41:52.779
but it would include
insects.

00:41:52.779 --> 00:42:00.630
But it would spiders and all kinds of things.
And -- he's friends with Hayao Miyazaki, you

00:42:00.630 --> 00:42:04.579
know, the anime, the
filmmaker.

00:42:04.579 --> 00:42:09.990
And both of them were, um, obsessed with insects
as children and in

00:42:09.990 --> 00:42:14.069
Miyazaki's movies, you can see very clearly
his interest in insects.

00:42:14.069 --> 00:42:17.970
And it continues, if you think of something
like Nausicaa, and other

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:22.910
movies, there's very often these very positive
representations of

00:42:22.910 --> 00:42:27.210
insects in them or insect-like beings, you
know?

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:33.390
And they both have argued that -- that these,
that insect eyes are

00:42:33.390 --> 00:42:36.930
something that you can develop from this close
attention to -- close

00:42:36.930 --> 00:42:39.599
attention to insects and spending time with
them.

00:42:39.599 --> 00:42:42.720
And the kind of attention that you get from
really looking at something

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:49.249
very, very small and recognizing that for
that small thing, there's a

00:42:49.249 --> 00:42:53.749
tremendous amount of variation in the world.
So that even the category like insects itself

00:42:53.749 --> 00:42:58.280
just does -- well, this
might not be the way to put it, but something

00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:01.829
like, you know, I want to
say something like does violence to the individual

00:43:01.829 --> 00:43:04.450
insects involved but
that might not be quite, quite -- I mean they

00:43:04.450 --> 00:43:06.339
would say that it
probably does more violence to us than to

00:43:06.339 --> 00:43:08.369
insects because we don't see
the variety.

00:43:08.369 --> 00:43:13.170
And a category like insects or like nature
those are so general that we

00:43:13.170 --> 00:43:18.019
lose that sense of the individuality of the
beings.

00:43:18.019 --> 00:43:23.039
And one of the things that Yoro said to me
was that for each insect --

00:43:23.039 --> 00:43:26.359
it's not just that every tree is different
but every leaf is different.

00:43:26.359 --> 00:43:30.200
And that if you can develop that kind of attention
to the -- to the

00:43:30.200 --> 00:43:36.150
difference in the individuality of things,
then in his mind that can

00:43:36.150 --> 00:43:38.910
also extend to more of an appreciation for
the individuality and

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:42.201
differences amongst people and more sort of
tolerance and respect for

00:43:42.201 --> 00:43:46.550
people that can you also have from your relationship
with insects but

00:43:46.550 --> 00:43:52.880
you can also see how the effects of more large
scale things say

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:56.049
something like climate change has effect on
tiny, tiny things too.

00:43:56.049 --> 00:43:59.549
If you're studying something as small as insects,
then you can see the

00:43:59.549 --> 00:44:02.869
effects of these large things on something
like an individual leaf

00:44:02.869 --> 00:44:06.519
rather than say just a forest and that will
give you more of a sense of --

00:44:06.519 --> 00:44:10.599
of the intensity of the effects and the breadth
of the effects as well.

00:44:10.599 --> 00:44:14.931
So that's one of the ways in which you start
to see the relationship

00:44:14.931 --> 00:44:17.539
between large and small.
For other people, of course, you know tiny,

00:44:17.539 --> 00:44:21.160
tiny things are the best
place to see a microcosm of the whole universe

00:44:21.160 --> 00:44:24.640
because it's in there
you see the tremendous detail.

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:28.869
And I suppose like the wonders of mysteries
of all things in many ways

00:44:28.869 --> 00:44:31.339
right?
Because as you get smaller and smaller it

00:44:31.339 --> 00:44:34.220
becomes actually harder and
harder in many ways to explain things.

00:44:34.220 --> 00:44:41.089
You might say, well, it's all DNA or so whatever.
You might find the tiniest molecular unit

00:44:41.089 --> 00:44:44.670
can you find that will be the
formative unit but fundamentally that really

00:44:44.670 --> 00:44:47.349
doesn't explain very much
about the mechanics.

00:44:47.349 --> 00:44:51.690
And there's some -- an awful lot of other
things which are left out of

00:44:51.690 --> 00:44:52.690
